results.notes:
I found these small clumps of orange/red strands with what appear to be fruiting bodies at the tips while examining bark samples for my photography; I enjoy taking pictures of lichens. The strands are approximately 2mm long, or a little more if it were stretched straight.

The trees they were growing on are mature deciduous trees, old trees, even, and around eye height on the trunk. I’ll be returning to gather more information and I’ll update this as possible if it turns out to be interesting. I’ve kept two specimens for now, one removed from its substrate, another intact on a sample of bark. I’m a bit vague on the tree involved because I collected several samples on a walk, and I didn’t isolate them. I wasn’t expecting anything new. When I first spotted it under my microscope, I thought some flower stamens had blown onto the bark and become trapped, but then I found more, and I extricated one to take a better look.

Updated with three new pictures. The first is the same specimen as in the original pictures, somewhat drier, now. The second and third are of the sample I removed from its bark, and they’re much drier now than when found.

results.notes:
Nearly two dozen emerging and mature fruit bodies on the side of a dirt road with limestone gravel in remote area, not often traveled. All were growing out of the dirt between the limestone gravel. Not on wood! The gravel itself was very rounded, indicating to me that it had been on dirt road a very long time and had been eroded by the weather and soil acidity. Cap dusty rose pink with umbo, slightly darker toward the center. Gills white without visible edge coloration, not attached to stem. Stem soft, translucent, pinched, dull, pale, with hint of pink on some. I have enough dried ones to share if you can guarantee me a good sequence and comparison with the Blue and brown more frequently seen here and mentioned in M of the RC by Noah and Christian.
